{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17614866","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17614866"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T14:49:13+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T14:49:13+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16377"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16377","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16377"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9068"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"64925"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9068","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9068"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16377"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"50359"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4911"},{"type":"tags","id":"4930"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"10350"},{"type":"tags","id":"10351"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"21556"},{"type":"contributions","id":"21559"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"64925","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/64925"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 45-year-old man is admitted to hospital following a brainstem stroke. Understanding the anatomical distribution of brainstem functions is critical for localising the lesion.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following functions is primarily mediated by the brainstem reticular system above the level of the mid-pons?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Respiratory control","Blood pressure regulation","Gastrointestinal motility","Cardiovascular reflexes","Oculomotor control"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe brainstem reticular system has distinct functional regions that are anatomically organised. Understanding this organisation is crucial for localising brainstem lesions.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOculomotor control\u003C/strong\u003E is primarily mediated by structures above the mid-pons, including the reticular formation of the midbrain and upper pons. This region contains important nuclei for eye movements including the paramedian pontine reticular formation (PPRF) and rostral interstitial nucleus of the medial longitudinal fasciculus (riMLF).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBlood pressure regulation\u003C/strong\u003E is primarily controlled by centres in the medulla, specifically the rostral ventrolateral medulla (RVLM) and nucleus tractus solitarius (NTS). These centres are well below the level of the mid-pons.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERespiratory control\u003C/strong\u003E is also mediated by centres in the medulla, including the pre-B\u00f6tzinger complex and other components of the ventral respiratory group. The pontine respiratory group in the lower pons also contributes but is below the mid-pons level.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGastrointestinal motility\u003C/strong\u003E is controlled by centres in the lower brainstem, particularly the dorsal motor nucleus of the vagus in the medulla, which provides parasympathetic innervation to the gut.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECardiovascular reflexes\u003C/strong\u003E such as baroreceptor and chemoreceptor responses are integrated in the medulla, particularly in the nucleus tractus solitarius and surrounding regions.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThis anatomical organisation reflects an evolutionary pattern where more primitive functions (breathing, blood pressure, digestion) are controlled by lower brainstem centres, while more recently evolved functions (eye movements, consciousness) are controlled by upper brainstem regions.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The upper brainstem reticular system primarily controls arousal, consciousness, and eye movements","The lower brainstem (medulla and lower pons) controls vital autonomic functions including breathing, blood pressure, and digestion","The mid-pons represents an important anatomical transition point between upper and lower brainstem functions"],"references":["Sakai K, Yokota H, Akazawa K, Yamada K. Brainstem white matter tracts and the control of eye movements. Semin Ultrasound CT MR. 2014 Oct;35(5):517-26. doi: 10.1053/j.sult.2014.06.009. Epub 2014 Jun 24. PMID: 25217303.","Balslev D, Mitchell AG, Faria PJM, Priba L, Macfarlane JA. Proprioceptive contribution to oculomotor control in humans. Hum Brain Mapp. 2022 Nov;43(16):5081-5090. doi: 10.1002/hbm.26080. Epub 2022 Sep 22. PMID: 36135800; PMCID: PMC9582377.","Singh, V. (2024).\u00a0Textbook of Clinical Neuroanatomy-E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences.","Michael-Titus, A. T., \u0026 Shortland, P. (2022).\u00a0The Nervous System, E-Book: The Nervous System, E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"50359"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16377"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"50359","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/50359"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-11-24T21:47:41+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-11-24T21:48:11+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9068"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"64925"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null